  "texts": [
    "The first track (T1) relies on assuming a fixed sampling budget at the evaluation stage while allowing for an arbitrary number of cost function evaluations.",
    "In contrast, the second track (T2) assumes we only have access to a limited number of cost function evaluations, which is the case for applications where the cost estimation is expensive.",
    "We also study the impact of the degree of data available to the models for their training.",
    "Our results have demonstrated that QCBMs are the most efficient in the scarce-data regime and, in particular, in T2.",
    "In general, QCBMs showcase a competitive diversity of solutions compared to the other state-of-the-art generative models in all the tracks and datasets considered here."
  ],
